  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Max Area of Island\n\nReturn the largest size of a connected component of `1` cells in a binary grid.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: grid = [[1,1,0],[0,1,1],[1,0,0]]\nOutput: 4\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: grid = [[0,0],[0,0]]\nOutput: 0\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: grid = [[1]]\nOutput: 1\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Inputs are sized for local offline execution.\n- Return values follow the method description.",
  "editorial": "Use the graph structure directly: traverse reachable states, maintain visited or distance state, and update the answer when each node or cell is settled.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maxAreaOfIsland(self, grid):\n        rows, cols = len(grid), len(grid[0])\n        def dfs(r, c):\n            if r < 0 or c < 0 or r == rows or c == cols or grid[r][c] == 0:\n                return 0\n            grid[r][c] = 0\n            return 1 + dfs(r + 1, c) + dfs(r - 1, c) + dfs(r, c + 1) + dfs(r, c - 1)\n        return max(dfs(r, c) for r in range(rows) for c in range(cols))\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Model the state explicitly.",
    "Prefer linear or near-linear graph traversal when possible."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def maxAreaOfIsland(self, grid):\n        pass\n"
  },
